title: Introduction to Currying and Partial Application
challengeType: 1
forumTopicId: 301232
dashedName: introduction-to-currying-and-partial-application
--description--
The arity of a function is the number of arguments it requires Currying a function means to convert a function of N arity into N functions of arity 1 In other words, it restructures a function so it takes one argument, then returns another function that takes the next argument, and so on Here's an example:
```js
function unCurried(x, y) {
return x + y;
}
function curried(x) {
return function(y) {
return x + y;
}
}
const curried = x => y => x + y
curried(1)(2)
```
curried(1)(2) would return 3 This is useful in your program if you can't supply all the arguments to a function at one time You can save each function call into a variable, which will hold the returned function reference that takes the next argument when it's available Here's an example using the curried function in the example above:
js
const funcForY = curried(1);
console log(funcForY(2)); // 3
Similarly, partial application can be described as applying a few arguments to a function at a time and returning another function that is applied to more arguments Here's an example:
```js
function impartial(x, y, z) {
return x + y + z;
}
const partialFn = impartial bind(this, 1, 2);
partialFn(10); // 13
```
